kets, government, and educational achievement. Their message is that neither markets nor government alone will guarantee freedom, equality, achievement, or community. If choice is to improve education and advance equality, then educational policy cannot be placed on automatic and left to the "free" market. Rather, choice policy must be deliberately directed toward meeting these goals, and this book shows how that could be accomplished.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEducation and statezUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 0aSchool choicezUnited States. 4aEducation : Education Policy and Leadership. 4aEducation : Educational Assessment and Evaluation. 4aEducation : Philosophy of Education. 4aEducation : Social Context of Education. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 7aEDUCATION / Decision-Making & Problem Solving.2bisacsh1 aAbowitz, Kathleen Knight, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Courtney A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrighouse, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeinberg, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeinberg, Walter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGordon, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowe, Kenneth R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLubienski, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLubienski, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNdimande, Bekisizwe S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReich, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScott, Janelle T., econt